         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25, WILTON PLACE. S.W. ¶ March 10 /72 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ I write a few lines to say that a box is packed and I believe sent off to you from Kew containing — besides some parcels which were lying there...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">72.03.10</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M3, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne. </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times, Times; ">25, WILTON PLACE. S.W.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">March 10 /72</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I write a few lines to say that a box is packed and I believe sent off to you from Kew containing — besides some parcels which were lying there for you, — your <name key="Thymeleae">Thymeleae</name> and <name key="Santalaceae">Santalaceae</name> which I trust you will receive safely</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am now in the midst of <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name>.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Years later, Joseph Hooker told Henry Hance that Bentham found M's work on <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name> 'terribly bad' in places; Hance expressed himself surprised because he expected M's work to be sound, though he conceded that he had the 'continental predilection for multiplying genera' (H. Hance to J. Hooker, 15 October 1878, RBG Kew, Directors' Correspondence 150/553-554). M differed with both Bentham and Hooker about the systematic position of <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name>, arguing that it was artificial to maintain them among the Monochlamydeae: see, for example, M to G. Bentham, 24 February 1865;  G. Bentham to M, 25 April 1865 (in this edition as 65-04-25a); M to G Bentham, 8 November 1882; and M to J. Hooker, 1 October 1882.</p>
               </note> I have done Euphorbia <name key="Poranthera">Poranthera</name> and <name key="Micrantheum">Micrantheum</name> I cannot say I quite approve of what Baillon has done as to your species<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Baillon (1866).</p>
               </note> I consider his E. chamoesyce<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">E. chamaesyce?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> E. Ferdinandi and E. Dallachyana as all referrible to E. Drummondii a species spread over all Australia and which there replaces our E. chamoesyce but in which I by no means recognise the true E. chamoesyce with which I am so familiar — the latter is strictly annual almost always pubescent and has a different aspect owing to the prevailing shape and texture of the leaves from the Australian one which is constantly glabrous forms after the first year a perennial stock and has rather thickish leaves. I do not think you have the true chamoesyce in Australia even as a weed of cultivation Baillon's E. Sharkoensis is the typical E. myrtoides E. vaccaria Baill. does not appear to me to differ from E. australis. Boissier (who had not seen typical specimens) mistook Hooker and Arnott's E. ramosissima which is Boissier's E. Chamissonis and Boissier's E. ramosissima must retain his former name of E. Sparrmani<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">E. Sparrmanni</seg>? cf. Boissier (1862), p. 14.</p>
               </note> I cannot guess at what Boissiers E. Brownii can be<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Error for Baillon's? See Baillon (1866), pp 290-1, and Bentham (1863-78) vol. 6, p. 46.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I do not at all agree with Muell. Arg [&amp;] Baillon in distinguishing <name key="Micranthea%20hexandra">Micranthea hexandra</name> generically from M ericoides<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Müller (1866), p. 195 and Baillon (1866), p. 326 place <seg style="font-style: italic; ">M. hexandra</seg> in <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Caletia</seg>.</p>
               </note> — both have carunculate seeds — the position of the lobes of the rudimentary ovary of M ericoides is merely the result of the nondevelopment of three of the stamens the relative position of the lobes of the ovary in the female flowers is the same in both species M hexandra varies with 6 to 9 stamens and in the number and shape of the lobes of the rudimentary ovary</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I shall have to include in the present volume Monocotyledons as far as <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name> and perhaps <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name> themselves and should feel much obliged by your forwarding the specimens I shall not however get on very rapidly for I have many other things on hand</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>We have received at times most of the numbers of your 7th vol of Fragmenta and proof slips of what I suppose is the whole of the remainder but no complete copy, and what is in slips is of course uncorrected and unpaged so that it cannot be quoted.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B71.12.03 was the final part of Volume 7; the index, B71.13.08, is undated.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Trusting your affairs that troubled you so much are now going on satisfactorily believe me</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever yours sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">The true American E. hypericifolia is not as far as I can see in Australia<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">Sentence written separately at top of p. 2 of letter.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Baron F. v. Mueller</p>
